<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-282-549  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 282 549.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  Jan 1989 v6 n1 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Banks react to FDIC guidelines on pc security. (Federal DepositInsurance Corp)</TITLE><AUTHOR>DeBow, Yvette.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp (FDIC) is concerned over risksassociated with end-user computing.andP;  The FDIC has issued strongwarnings on computer procedures and guidelines for electronic dataprocessing examiners.andP;  This, together with notoriety caused by theNov 1988 virus attack on the Defense Department's Internet system,is pushing bankers toward sounder security policies.andP;  Regulatoryagencies say banks should address such areas as documentation,audit procedures physical and logical access, and backup andcontingency planning in their security programs.andP;  Tompkins CountyTrust Co is now marketing the Banking Micromanual ($595), ageneric version of its in-house policy guideline tool fordocumenting microcomputer use.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Tompkins County Trust Co. (publishing).andO;Topic:     BankingSecurityMicrocomputersManagement of EDPGovernment RegulationUnited States. Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.andO;End Users.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>